# Architectural Blueprint and AI Governance Strategy for AutoCompt via Google Antigravity

## Introduction to Agentic Governance in Software Ecosystems
The integration of autonomous coding assistants into complex, living enterprise codebases represents a profound paradigm shift in modern software engineering. As software systems evolve from repositories exclusively authored by human developers to dynamic environments co-authored by artificial intelligence, the necessity for rigorous architectural governance, explicitly defined constraints, and deterministic execution protocols becomes absolutely paramount. The "AutoCompt" ecosystem, a sophisticated Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) platform tailored specifically for the nuanced requirements of the Quebec real estate and property management market, presents a uniquely challenging environment for an autonomous AI agent. Constructed on a modern, highly interactive technology stack comprising React 19, TypeScript, Vite, Express, Firebase, and Gemini AI, the application is responsible for managing intricate financial logic, enforcing strict Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) matrices, maintaining precise visual identity guidelines, and ensuring stringent regional legal compliance regarding data privacy and property management statutes.

However, an inspection of the current architectural state of the AutoCompt repository reveals a critical structural vulnerability: the presence of a monolithic App.tsx file encompassing 23,573 lines of code. This single file houses an overwhelming majority of the core application logic, routing instructions, and state management protocols. During agentic augmentation, such a massive monolith poses a severe operational risk. When unconstrained, large language models and autonomous coding agents are highly susceptible to context loss, unauthorized and sweeping refactoring, and the destructive overwriting of functional, verified code. To completely mitigate these systemic risks, the deployment of Google Antigravity 2.0 requires a meticulously engineered set of persistent rules, specialized skills, and sequential workflows. Unlike traditional, single-threaded conversational coding assistants, Antigravity operates not as a simplistic chatbot, but as a persistent software organism capable of running multiple specialized agents in parallel, executing localized browser-based verification, and autonomously navigating complex directory structures to prove feature functionality. This inherent power requires equivalent restraint. This comprehensive research report provides an exhaustive strategy for encoding the AutoCompt Golden Rules, the non-negotiable UI/UX directives, and the critical legal compliance constraints into the Antigravity configuration matrix. By establishing explicit permission tiers, progressive knowledge disclosure, and directory-targeted behavioral triggers, the integrity of the AutoCompt ecosystem can be rigorously preserved while simultaneously leveraging the rapid iteration and problem-solving capabilities of an agent-first development environment.

## The Google Antigravity Structural Framework
To prevent an AI coding assistant from inadvertently deleting verified modules, corrupting established design patterns, or hallucinating incorrect tax logic, the governance model must move beyond reactive, prompt-based instructions into proactive, repository-level rule enforcement. Relying on a developer to manually remind the AI of the application's constraints during every interaction is inefficient and highly prone to error. Google Antigravity provides a sophisticated, tri-layered customization architecture designed specifically to address this challenge, consisting of Rules, Workflows, and Skills. Understanding the precise function and configuration of these three distinct layers is the foundational step in protecting and modernizing the AutoCompt codebase.

### The Tri-Layered Customization Architecture
The first layer of the Antigravity framework is composed of Rules, which function as contextual constraints. Rules act as the persistent foundational boundaries that continuously guide the agent's behavior at the foundational prompt level. They are stored as standard Markdown files within the .agents/rules/ directory of the active workspace and are strictly limited to 12,000 characters per file to ensure processing efficiency. Rules utilize a YAML frontmatter block at the beginning of the document to define their core metadata and, crucially, their execution triggers. This is where the non-negotiable dictates, such as the prohibition against deleting code or the requirement to use specific color palettes, are permanently encoded.

The second layer consists of Workflows, which define procedural sequences. While Rules provide continuous behavioral guidance, Workflows provide a structured, deterministic sequence of interconnected steps for the agent to follow. Stored as YAML or Markdown files within the .agents/workflows/ directory, these sequences are ideal for orchestrating complex, multi-stage operations that carry high risk, such as the systematic dismantling and refactoring of the massive App.tsx monolith, or the execution of automated deployment pipelines that require rigorous testing gates before completion.

The third layer comprises Skills, which represent modular capabilities designed to address the critical problem of context saturation. Indiscriminately loading an AI agent with entire codebases and hundreds of specialized tools leads to "Tool Bloat," resulting in high latency, financial waste, and "context rot," where the model becomes confused by an overwhelming volume of irrelevant data. Instead of forcing the model to memorize every technical requirement—such as the specific computational formatting of a complex Quebec tax form—Skills package this procedural knowledge into modular units located in the .agents/skills/ directory. Through a process of progressive disclosure, the agent is initially exposed only to a lightweight menu of metadata. It loads the heavy procedural instructions and scripts only when the user's explicit intent matches the skill's YAML description.

### Deterministic Rule Activation Protocols
For a financial and legally binding application like AutoCompt, the application of rules by the AI agent must be absolute and deterministic. Antigravity supports four primary activation types defined within the YAML frontmatter of the rule files, allowing developers to precisely target when and how constraints are applied.

The Always On protocol (alwaysApply: true or trigger: always_on) mandates that the rule is injected into the agent's context window for every single interaction, regardless of the task. This protocol is mandatory for AutoCompt's designated Golden Rules, ensuring they cannot be bypassed under any circumstances. The Glob Pattern protocol (match: "pattern") provides targeted activation, triggering the rule only when the agent explores or manipulates files that match a specific directory pattern (e.g., src/components/**/*.tsx). This mechanism is highly effective for enforcing the specific UI/UX design directives without cluttering the agent's context when it is working on backend server logic. The Model Decision protocol relies on the agent using natural language reasoning to determine if the rule is relevant to the current task. While flexible, this activation type should be strictly avoided for critical security and architectural rules within AutoCompt, as it introduces probabilistic variation into what must be deterministic constraints. Finally, the Manual protocol ensures a rule remains entirely dormant until explicitly invoked by the developer via an @ mention in the prompt interface.

## Encoding the AutoCompt Golden Rules
The project directives establish three fundamental "Golden Rules" that dictate the structural integrity of the AutoCompt platform. To guarantee that the Antigravity AI agent respects these boundaries implicitly, these rules must be translated into machine-readable constraints and encoded as Always On global rules utilizing explicit permission tiers. This configuration strategy divides the agent's potential actions into three distinct categories: operations that are allowed autonomously without human intervention, operations requiring explicit human confirmation before execution, and operations that are strictly forbidden under any context.

### Translating Rule 1: The Zero Deletion Policy
The first directive states: "Never delete existing UI modules. Hide them using conditional rendering based on the active profile, but never remove the underlying code (e.g., never delete Syndicat modules when working on Prospecteur)." This rule directly addresses one of the most common and catastrophic failure modes of autonomous AI assistants: the tendency to "nuke" functional, working code when attempting to optimize logic or respond to a narrow prompt. When human developers request a small change, AI assistants frequently lose track of the broader application context, overwriting essential instructions or interpreting a requested modification as a complete replacement rather than an addition.

To enforce this absolute boundary, an AGENTS.md file (or a specialized rule file located at .agents/rules/01-golden-rules.md) must be established with the highest priority configuration. The YAML frontmatter must dictate continuous, workspace-wide application across the entire React ecosystem. The body of the rule must explicitly define the "Never" tier : The agent is absolutely forbidden from utilizing terminal commands such as rm, unlink, or executing Git commands that result in the permanent deletion of any file located within the src/components/ directory.

Furthermore, the rule must not simply forbid action; it must explicitly dictate the required architectural pattern for module management. The agent must be instructed to utilize the existing rbacConfig.ts matrix to conditionally render views. For example, the agent must write logic such as if (!hasAccess(activeProfile, 'Syndicat')) return null; rather than excising the logic entirely. By embedding this operational philosophy directly into the persistent system instructions, the agent's continuous semantic compaction process will inherently reject any proposed operations or execution paths that involve file deletion, preserving the integrity of the 75% complete codebase.

### Translating Rules 2 and 3: Database Authority and Universal Modules
Rule 2 specifies that Google Drive functions as the core database for all file storage, mandating that all modules rely on the existing workspace integration and that data is strictly separated by Company/Building hierarchies. Rule 3 mandates the concept of Universal Modules, dictating that the Scanner IA (Factures), Dossiers Fiscaux, Sofi AI Assistant, and the Settings Gear must exist and remain accessible for all five user profiles.

Enforcing these rules requires the configuration to construct a robust "defense in depth" strategy. To satisfy Rule 2, the Antigravity agent must be provided with an instruction that permanently forbids the replacement of the Google Drive integration with alternative file storage mechanisms. For instance, the agent might autonomously decide that direct Firebase Storage bucket uploads are more efficient for a new module. The rule must preemptively block this reasoning, dictating that any module manipulating, uploading, or retrieving files must import and interface exclusively with the established driveService.ts utility.

To satisfy Rule 3 regarding Universal Modules, the rule must ensure that any automated refactoring of the Sidebar or Main Navigation components includes hardcoded guarantees. The agent must be instructed that the components rendering these four specific modules are invariant; they must remain unconditionally rendered in the layout wrapper, completely bypassing standard RBAC filtering arrays if necessary, ensuring that no profile update or permission tweak accidentally hides the core AI or settings functionality.

## Navigating and Enforcing the RBAC Matrix
The AutoCompt system currently relies on a sophisticated and explicit access matrix defined within src/lib/rbacConfig.ts, which governs the permissions and module visibility for five distinct professional profiles. The primary danger during agent-led development is the unintentional exposure of restricted modules to incorrect user profiles, or the failure to implement the required conditional logic within newly generated features. To completely mitigate this risk, the Antigravity configuration must enforce a mandatory verification loop. A rule must be defined stating that before the agent implements any new React view or modifies the navigation sidebar, it must first execute an automated read of the rbacConfig.ts file to verify its current state against the proposed changes.

### Profile-Specific Directives and Constraints
The rule matrix must explicitly define the expected logic and operational focus for each of the five profiles to guide the AI agent during feature implementation and UI generation:

| Profile | Application Focus | Permitted Modules & Agent Directives |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Prospecteur Immobilier** | Speed, mobility, fast invoicing in the field. | Modules: Scanner IA, Kilométrage GPS, Facturation, Bureau à domicile, Contrats & Résolutions, Sous-traitants, Déclaration TPS/TVQ, Conciliation bancaire, Taxes & Assurances, Tenue de livres. Directive: Strict enforcement of the $30,000 TPS/TVQ registration lock. |
| **Investisseur Immobilier** | Asset tracking, multi-tenant transparency. | Directive: Implement branching UI logic based on onboarding filter. If "Gestion déléguée", enforce Oversight Mode. If "Autogestion", enable Tenue de livres and the 100% strictly validated Répartition Fiscale engine. |
| **Flippeur Immobilier** | Budget control, fast property flips, contractors. | Modules: Includes DocuLegal and Heures & Paie. Directive: Restrict Heures & Paie strictly to manual entry interfaces; prohibit the agent from generating external payroll API integrations. |
| **Gestionnaire Immobilier** | Multi-tenant architecture, property administration. | Directive: Enforce multi-tier Google Drive folder structure mapping (Client -> Sub-folder Property 1 -> Tenue de livres). Require 1-click sharing functionality for financial ledgers. |
| **Syndicat de Copropriété** | Co-owner transparency, legal compliance. | Modules: Gestion des Cotisations, Tableau de Transparence, Loi 16 & Carnet d'entretien, SyndicAI. Directive: Prioritize immutable ledger creation for all compliance modules. |

A deeper analysis of these profiles reveals complex dependencies that the AI agent must be programmed to handle. For the Prospecteur Immobilier, the directive states that the Déclaration TPS/TVQ module must include a visual tracker alerting the user at $27,000 and locking compliance at $30,000. This is not arbitrary; the $30,000 threshold represents the exact point under Quebec law where a business loses "small supplier" status and is legally mandated to register for GST/QST. The agent must be instructed that this tracker cannot merely look at a single invoice. The logic generated must establish a Firebase listener that aggregates the total worldwide taxable supplies (including any associated entities) across a given calendar quarter and the four preceding quarters. The agent must write strict validation logic preventing further invoice generation without a registered tax number once the threshold is breached.

For the Investisseur Immobilier, the agent must recognize the internal state split within the profile. It must programmatically verify the onboarding filter state within the user's Firebase document. If Gestion déléguée is active, the UI must route exclusively to the Oversight Mode. If Autogestion is active, the UI must render the operational modules, including the explicitly read-only Tableau de Transparence. Crucially, when the agent develops the Répartition Fiscale engine, the rule must mandate an invariant mathematical check in the frontend form and backend validation: the distribution of fiscal responsibility among co-owners must add up to exactly 100%, rejecting any state change that calculates to 99.9% or 100.1%.

For the Gestionnaire Immobilier, the agent must strictly adhere to a multi-tenant folder architecture when manipulating the driveService.ts. The AI cannot be allowed to dump all client files into a single repository; it must procedurally generate and verify the existence of the Client -> Sub-folder Property 1 -> Tenue de livres hierarchy via Google Drive API calls before uploading any financial documents.

### Expansion of the Super Admin Panel Metrics
The existing SuperAdminPanel.tsx is functional but requires significant expansion based on the user's explicit metrics requirements. An Antigravity workflow can be structured to safely enhance this critical administrative interface without exposing sensitive backend routes. The agent must be instructed via the workflow to aggregate real-time API Token usage per profile, compile a comprehensive Client Directory encompassing emails, phone numbers, and active profiles, track the total volume of Legal Documents generated, and meticulously manage Beta Phase metrics. This Beta Phase tracking must include logic to parse the database for free month status expiration dates, survey completion flags, and suggested pricing data inputted by early adopters. The workflow must ensure that the agent establishes safe, read-only queries to the Firebase backend when constructing these administrative dashboards, preventing any accidental mutation of core user data during the aggregation process.

## Strict UI/UX Directives and The SOFI Entity Configuration
AutoCompt relies on a meticulously defined visual hierarchy, demanding absolute adherence to ensure user trust within a professional financial and real estate environment. The core directives specify rigid iconography styles, a highly specific global dark mode color palette, dynamic glassmorphism mechanics, and strict anatomical rules for the visualization of the "SOFI" AI entity. AI assistants, when tasked with creating new UI components, frequently attempt to "improve" designs by introducing unauthorized gradients, altering border radii, or utilizing unapproved color variables. This creative liberty must be strictly prohibited through targeted Glob rules.

### The Core Styling and Iconography Rules
A dedicated rule file (e.g., .agents/rules/02-ui-ux-directives.md) must be instantiated within the workspace. This rule must utilize a Glob pattern match: `**/*.tsx` to ensure it triggers whenever a React component is analyzed, modified, or created. The primary instruction must categorically forbid the use of solid or filled icons across the entire platform. The agent must be constrained to utilize strictly linear, outline-style iconography, maintaining a clean, wireframe aesthetic. The rule must explicitly state: "NO filled areas, NO solid glyphs, and NO gradients within shapes are permitted for any SVG or icon library import."

Furthermore, the global color palette instructions must be explicitly defined using precise Tailwind utility class formats, matching the existing codebase standards. The agent must be instructed that the use of pure black (#000000 or bg-black)